<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910919-0090</DOCNO><DOCID>910919-0090.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   U.S. Workers in Toyota Ad</HL><DATE>09/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   HMC SAA TOYOY</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)AUTOMOBILES (AUT)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)KENTUCKY (KY)NORTH AMERICA (NME)OHIO (OH)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   DETROIT -- Toyota Motor Corp. will step up its campaign toportray itself as a U.S. car company with the firsttelevision commercials to star workers at its Georgetown,Ky., assembly plant.   The new Toyota TV commercials, which are reminiscent ofthe folksy advertisements that General Motors Corp.'s Saturndivision ran last fall, mark the first time a Japanese automaker has shown its U.S. factory and workers in a TV ad.</LP><TEXT>   Toyota has a long-running national print campaign thatfeatures its charitable activities in the U.S. Honda MotorCo. has a national print campaign advertising that the HondaAccord is made in Marysville, Ohio. Nissan Motor Co. airedcommercials in the Midwest touting the &quot;all-new,American-built Nissan Sentra.&quot;   But Toyota's latest advertising is an apparent attempt toblunt the &quot;Buy American&quot; pitches by Detroit's Big Three automakers. Toyota's television spot opens with horses and showsworkers assembling cars in the Georgetown plant. The scenesclosely parallel the images GM used to launch its Saturndivision, which is aimed at taking sales away from Toyota andother Japanese manufacturers.   The new Toyota commercials were created by the Torrance,Calif., office of Saatchi andamp; Saatchi DFS/Pacific, a unit ofLondon's Saatchi andamp; Saatchi Co.</TEXT></DOC>